{{Infobox person | name = Ioannis D. Evrigenis | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | residence = | nationality = American | alma_mater = [[Grinnell College]] | occupation = Professor | years_active = | employer = [[Tufts University]] | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | religion = | denomination = | spouse = | children = | website = }} '''Ioannis D. Evrigenis''' is a [[Greek Americans|Greek-American]] [[Political philosophy|political philosopher]]. He is a Professor of [[Political science|Political Science]] at [[Tufts University]].
== Biography == Evrigenis received his B.A. in political science from [[Grinnell College]] in 1993.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://as.tufts.edu/politicalscience/people/faculty/evrigenis|title=People – Ioannis D. Evrigenis|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Tufts University]] Department of Political Science|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322044906/http://as.tufts.edu/politicalscience/people/faculty/evrigenis|archive-date=March 22, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=}}</ref> He earned a M.Sc. from the [[London School of Economics|London School of Economics & Political Science]] in 1994.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://emerald.tufts.edu/~ievrig01/cv.html|title=Curriculum Vitae|last=|first=|date=|website=Ioannis D. Evrigenis – Personal Website|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> From 1994 to 1996, Evrigenis served as an [[artillery]] [[quartermaster]] in the [[Hellenic Army]], holding the rank of [[second lieutenant]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10427/44960|title=Political science professor examines world's ancient questions – with a fresh perspective|last=Cooper|first=Jackson|date=April 7, 2008|work=[[The Tufts Daily]]|access-date=March 22, 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> In 2002, he received an M.A. in political science from [[Harvard University]].<ref name=":1" /> In 2005, Evrigenis earned his Ph.D. in political science from Harvard.<ref name=":0" /> He received the Herrnstein Prize for his doctoral dissertation, "'Carthage Must be Saved': Fear of Enemies and Collective Action."<ref name=":1" />
In the fall of 2005, Evrigenis came to [[Tufts University]] as an Assistant Professor of Political Science.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10427/44589|title=Political science dept. showcases new talent|last=Sawicki|first=Kristen|date=February 25, 2005|work=[[The Tufts Daily]]|access-date=March 22, 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> He was promoted to the position of Associate Professor in 2010, and he earned the full title of Professor in 2015.<ref name=":1" /> In the fall of 2015, Evrigenis also became the chair of Tufts' Department of Classics.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ase.tufts.edu/classics/people/|title=Department of Classics: People|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Tufts University]] Department of Classics|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907233744/http://ase.tufts.edu/classics/people/|archive-date=September 7, 2015|dead-url=|access-date=|quote=Ioannis Evrigenis, Department Chair, Director of Graduate Studies}}</ref> He served in the role for three years before ceding the position to R. Bruce Hitchner following the 2018 spring semester.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/news/2018/02/13/professors-submit-proposal-replace-pjs-major-civic-studies/|title=Professors submit proposal to replace PJS major with civic studies|last=Lala|first=Simran|date=February 13, 2018|work=[[The Tufts Daily]]|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726011026/https://tuftsdaily.com/news/2018/02/13/professors-submit-proposal-replace-pjs-major-civic-studies/|archive-date=July 26, 2018|dead-url=no|language=en-US|quote=...and Professor of political science and Classics Department chair Ioannis Evrigenis...}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ase.tufts.edu/classics/people/|title=Department of Classics: People|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Tufts University]] Department of Classics|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723182500/http://ase.tufts.edu/classics/people/|archive-date=July 26, 2018|dead-url=|access-date=|quote=R. Bruce Hitchner, Department Chair, Classics; Director, Archaeology Program}}</ref>
